{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_limbo_ver01/data/sn85025570/00383348390/1937120901/0612.xml":{"full_text":"THE REDWOOD GAZETTE\nPublished By\nREDWOOD GAZETTE PUB. CO., Inc.\nSCOTT SCHOEN, EDITOR\nEntered as Second Class Matter, at the\nPosteffice, Redwood Falls, Minnesota,\nunder Act of March B,* 1879.\n68 Years of Service to City and County\nMEMBER\nNational Editorial Association\nMinnesota Editorial Association\nRedwood County Press Association\nSubscription price $2 per year\nOutside United States $2.50\nGOVERNOR BENSON WENT OUT\nto California last week to help in another\nattempt to get Tom Mooney out of jail.\nWhich strikes us as a long way to go to get\ninto an argument.\n\nTHE THOMAS J. MOONEY AND\nWarren K. Billings convictions for murder\nin connection with the preparedness parade\nbombings in 1916 may or may not have been\njust. California courts evidently think\nthere was no mistake since the men are still\nin jail; but noisy efforts to obtain their re\nlease have been the hottest kind of political\nappeal to the radical labor vote for two de\ncades and Benson is only following the ex\nample of Floyd B. Olson in his efforts.\n\nTO MOST MINNESOTANS THE KIND\nof labor troubles we have had in Minnesota,\nparticularly Minneapolis, and the current\ntrouble there which led to the murder of a\nlabor leader, are considerably more import\nant. This week the Hennepin county at\ntorney was threatened and the demand\nmade that he \u201clay off\u201d investigations into\nthe brutal murder of Patrick J. Corcoran.\n\nIT IS TIME THE STATE ADMlNlS\ntration took an active interest in cleaning\nhouse on outside agitators and any local\ngangsters who pretend to be the friends of\nlabor. They must be driven out of organiz\ned labor and the state. Administration\nspeakers have much to say about Fascism\nbut intimidation of authorities, interference\nwith rights of men who are willing to work\nand forcing men to join organizations to\nprotect their jobs are fully as dangerous.\nMaybe there are men in jails who should\nbe out but there are many more out who\nshould be in.\n\nSINCE THE DAYS OF THE NRA,\nbusiness has demanded a let-up in spend\ning, a balanced budget and federal overtures\nof friendship as a basis for re-entry of pri\nvate capital into the business expansion\nfield and the achievement of the hope of a\nsound recovery financed by means other\nthan taxation and over zealous government\nspending.\nWhen business recently began to lag,\nthe president quite suddenly did an about\nface on federal policies and began efforts to\nwoo private monies out of hiding and into\nfields which would mean more private em\nployment and a general business revival.\nF. R. has called their bluff. It now remains\nto be seen whether big business is in reality\nany more ready to rally for an honest re\ncovery than it was in 1933 when the presi\ndent took office.\n\nTHE DECISION TO REVISE Gov\nernment policies, curtail spending and gen\nerally revamp the phases of the new deal\nwhich had the nation\u2019s business leaders see\ning spooks in every administration move is\nthe most encouraging factor in this month\u2019s\nnews.\nSeveral industrial leaders have found\nthemselves welcome at the white house\nwhere they might have got the busy signal\na few weeks back and obtained an attentive\near for plans to give business a boost and\nkeep it rolling by natural means rather than\ncontinued government priming which sooner\nor later would have caused the well to gc\ndry.\nThe truce between capital and govern\nment is gaining favor throughout the coun\ntry, many voters believing the middle road,\nmaintained by Wall Street and policed by\nthe government, is the smoothest to travel.\nMeanwhile at Portland, Oregon, on his trip\nlast week Governor Benson urged heavier\ntaxes for industry and the entry of the gov\nernment into more industrial fields. Will the\nDemocrats and Farmer-Laborites split in\nMinnesota over the newest new deal; or is\neverybody out of step but Elmer?\n\nTHE FIGHT TO ELIMINATE SUF\nfering from tuberculosis is by no means\nover; in fact depression factors of malnutri\ntion and poor housing have resulted in a\nloss of ground in recent years. There is\ngreater need today than ever before for dis\ncovery of infections early to save the indi\nvidual and protect others from infection.\nBuying Christmas seals helps in the cam\npaign.\n\nTHE STATE DIVISION OF GAME\nand fish is responsible for the guess that\none deer was shot for every two hunters\nwho purchased big game licenses this year.\nA good many hunters who returned with no\nvenison to show their neighbors hope the\ndepartment is more accurate when it makes\nup such statistical matters as budget esti\nmates.\n\nWE IN AMERICA ARE ORIGINAL\nabout names. Years ago they called them\npanics but when 1930 came along we dubbed\nthe tailspin a depression. Right now there\nis talk of the \u201crecession\u201d and if the budget\nisn\u2019t balanced and a lot of people encourag\ned to make their own livings, the next set\nback may be known as the concussion.\nREDWOOD FALLS IS NOT THE\nonly city in this section where a housing\nshortage is standing in the way of rapid\ngrowth. Talk to the residents of almost\nany good town or village and the report is\nthe same, persons waiting almost in line to\ngrab dwellings and apartments as they be\ncome empty, places rented and tenants an\nxious to get in even before foundations for\nnew homes are completed. It is a utopia for\nlandlords but there is another angle. New\ndwellings mean new property on the tax\nrolls, a division of the tax burden which\ncounts up when additions are extensive.\nLabor made possible by building operations\ntends to keep down relief rolls and stimu\nlates business which in turn brings more\nfamilies to town and makes it possible for\nyoung people to marry and start new fami\nlies, increasing the demand for homes.\nCapital now invested in homes and that\nlikely to go into, homes in the next few sea\nsons is safely and wisely placed. A more\naggressive government housing program\nlooks like a splendid scheme around which\nto rally business men in a renewed drive to\nward recovery.\n\nONE OF THE MYSTERIES OF THE\ndepression was how, while all around them\nother firms were failing or having difficul\nties, some firms managed to hold their own\nand in some instances, actually make pro\ngress. It has been attributed to going into\ncheaper lines in some instances but not all\nthe cheap line firms enjoyed the depression\nby any means. The secret might be found\nin the attitude of the firm management\nwhich naturally was reflected in employees.\nWhere the owner lost heart with the first\nsign of a slump and spent more time wor\nrying than in finding a solution to his diffi\nculties, the end was soon in sight. It\u2019s hard\nto lick a fellow who keeps his chin up and\nrefuses to flinch when a stiff blow hurts\nhim.\n\nPADDING THE EXPENSE ACCOUNT\nhas caused many an otherwise good travel\ning salesman to lose his job but we don\u2019t\nsuppose one ever tried to collect 20 cents\nper mile for traveling expenses. Congress,\nhowever, has the privilege and this week\nvoted $220,000 to pay for trips home for\nChristmas at 20 cents per mile for the round\ntrip. And here\u2019s the payoff: The senator\nor congressman can collect the mileage\nwhether he goes home or stays in Washing\nton. There was no filibuster to block this\nbit of burglary.\nj What Others Think j\nFOR MONTHS THE DAILY PAPERS\nplayed up the sit-down strikes of labor, but\nwhen big business stages a sit-down strike,\nas it has done the past few months, in order\nto frighten the country into demanding re\npeal of taxes, the conservative press doesn\u2019t\nplay that up at all. Yet big business\u2019 sit\ndown strike has cost the nation millions\nwhere labor\u2019s sit-down strike cost thous\nands.\u2014Park Region Echo (Alexandria.)\n\nMAYOR LEACH HAS BEEN HAVING\nslot machine trouble and other difficulties\nthat appear to have opened a slow leak in\nhis political balloon.\u2014Appleton Press.\n\nARMISTICE DAY WE SAW A WAR\nhero being led home by the ear by a 105-\npound wife. Such a life.\u2014Baudette Region.\n\nTHERE ARE MANY WHO ARE WON\ndering if the Minneapolis city administra\ntion and the police are so involved that the\nCorcoran murder will be allowed to go un\nsolved as were the murders of Guilford and\nLiggett.\u2014ltasca County Independent.\n\nFREQUENT WATER DRINKING, WE\nare told, will prevent one from getting stiff\nin the joints. No doubt it will, but most of\nthe joints don\u2019t seem to like customers who\ncome in and order only water.\u2014Minneota\nMascot.\n\nBILLY ROSE, A THEATRICAL PRO\nmoter, says as soon as he gets a divorce\nfrom Fanny Brice he is going to marry\nEleanor Holm Jarrett as soon as she gets a\ndivorce from Art Jarrett, orchestra leader.\nWho cares?\u2014Wadena Pioneer-Journal.\n\nIN 1935 WE IMPORTED 35,000,000\npounds of starch which should help stiffen\nthe backbones of those who believe in buy\ning from other countries rather than pro\nducing for ourselves.\u2014Wadena Pioneer-\nJournal.\n\nFIFTY YEARS AGO MOST CITIZENS\ndidn\u2019t have the \u201cadvantages\u201d we have to\nday, but they had a lot of time to enjoy\nthose they did have.\u2014Fergus Falls Tribune.\n\nTHIS FELLOW GARNER MAKES AN\nideal vice president. He never talks until\nhe has something to say, and then doesn\u2019t\nsay it.\u2014Benson Monitor.\n\nFOR EITHER A DEMOCRAT OR A\nRepublican to help elect a governor of the\nother party would be inconsistent with the\nnational welfare of his party, in spite of all\nthe arguments setting forth the necessity\nfor a change in Minnesota that might be ad\nvanced. The better course is for each party\nto make its own bid for power, and let the\nvoters make their own choice.\u2014Morris Tri\nbune.\n\nWE WONDER HOW MANY OF US\nwould be willing to exchange places with\nthose on the relief rolls. We know that most\nof them would be willing to trade places\nwith us and take a chance on making their\nway. Instead of looking for something to\ncomplain about, let us all be thankful thaf\nthings are not worse than they are.\u2014Madi\nson Independent Press.\nCongressman Kvale\nReports \u201cFumble\u201d in\nFarm Bill Struggle\nBy Paul John Kvale, M. C.\nThe big news this week for us\nof the agricultural districts is the\ndetermined fight of Senators\nBorah (Rep. Idaho), Austin\n(Rep.-Vt.) and King (Dem.-\nUtah). These gentlemen have all\ntaken up the cudgels in opposi\ntion to the proposed legislation.\nThe remarks of Senator Borah re\ngarding the proposed bill are\nhighly significant in view of the\nfact that he is generally acknow\nledged an authority on constitu\ntional law and one who consorted\nmost pleasantly with the presi\ndent at Boise last fall.\nProceeding to the record let us\nquote Senator Borah in part:\n\u201cThis will immediately subject\nthose who fail to sign contracts to\nthe disfavor of the government. I\nsay it is a punishment\u2014a dis\ntinct punishment\u2014to withhold\nsoil conservation payments and\nloans from farmers if they do not\ncontract under the new program.\u201d\nSenators Ellender (Lem.-la.)\nand McGill (Dem.-Kans.) argue\nthat the pending measure is not\nmore compulsory than the present\nsoil conservation program whose\nbenefit payments are conditioned\nupon farmers complying with the\napproved soil building and con\nserving practices. Borah replied\nas follows: \u201cI do not think one\nunconstitutional measure justifies\nanother. It is contrary to the\npublic interest if you are going to\nuse it as a club to drive the\nfarmer into this program. The\nidea of crop control and the phil\nosophy of the reduction of food\nstuffs in the midst of hunger ori\nginated in the previous admin\nistration. Mr. Hoover was the\nauthor of that doctrine. He was\nthe first man, not only in the\nhistory of the United States but\nin the history of the world, to\npropose a scarcity as a remedy\nfor economic ills, while the whole\nworld for 3,000 years has been\ninventing machinery and apply\ning itself in every way to produce\nmore and more in order that the\nhuman family may live in ordin\nary peace. If there is any glory\nin the philosophy which we are\nnow proposing to enact into law\nthat glory must be shared with\nthe previous president of the\nUnited States. I was opposed to\nit at that time; and I do not care\nwhere it comes from I am oppos\ned to it now.\u201d The senator then\nproceeded to predict that millions\nof people would go hungry this\nwinter and millions of children\nwould be kept out of school be\ncause of insufficient food and\nclothing.\nAt this point Senator Barkley\n(Dem.-Ky.) Majority Leader, in\nterrupted to ask: \u201cJust what is\nthe Senator\u2019s program for handl\ning this?\u201d Borah replied, \u201cBasical\nly I would, in the first place, pro\nceed to legislate on the theory\nof separating the domestic needs\nfrom the surplus needs. I would\nnot interfere with production. I\nwould leave that to the farmer.\nBut I would, as a government,\nwhere it was necessary to assist\nin disposing of these surpluses,\ntake the surplus off the market\nand separate it from the domes\ntic needs.\u201d Senator Barkley then\ninquired: \u201cWould that involve a\n(Continued on page seven)\nij Backward\nGlances j.\n5 YEARS AGO\nSheriff Kise left for Chappell,\nColorado, to bring back a car\nthief.\u2014Mrs. John Jackson and\nHoward Hudson were called to\nthe bedside of their father who\nwas critically injured in an auto\nmobile accident.\u2014The Redwood\nFalls Relief association raised\n$725.07. \u2014The annual winter con\ncert of the Scenic City band was\nheld at the Redwood theatre.\n$871.08 was distributed among\nRedwood county girls and boys\nwho showed livestock at the Jun\nior show in South St. Paul.\u2014\nCongressman Frank Clague was\none of the eight Minnesota con\ngressmen who voted in favor of\nProbitition repeal.\u2014 The alumni\ndinner was to be held in the Eng\nlish Lutheran church.\u2014 The Mor\ngan basketball team won its first\ngame of the season from Wabasso\n-37 to 5.\u2014515,000 was awarded to\nMiss Beth Morse in a verdict ren\ndered in Marshall.\u2014 N. R. Ryer\nson was appointed to the zoning\ncommittee of the Minnesota Lea\ngue of Minicipalities.\u2014Mrs. Eliza\nbeth Kirby of Sheridan township\ndied.\u2014George Datwyler of New\nAvon township was found dead\nin his car.\u2014Plans were made for\nmeat cutting demonstrations to be\nheld throughout the county.\n\n10 YEARS AGO\nOrson Wells, Redwood Falls\npioneer, died.\u2014H. W. Ward was\nreappointed postmaster.\u2014Three\nhundred twenty-five birds were\nexhibited at the annual Redwood\ncounty poultry show.\u2014V. A. Ben\njamin of Granite Falls bought the\nAlfstad bakery.\u2014Miss Katherine\nBall was taking nurses training at\nUniversity hospital.\u2014G. E. Mc-\nKay subscribed to the Gazette for\nthe fiftieth consecutive year.\u2014\nJoseph Lepeska, Olivia resident\ndied.\u2014The amateur corn show\nheld here was successful.\u2014Mrs.\nAugust Ortmann of Sanborn died.\n\u2014Lorenzo Ziegler of North Red\nwood was attending Carleton col\nlege.\u2014Mrs. Kellam was ill.\u2014\nBert Lamphere, mail carrier,\nthanked his patrons for keeping\ntheir walks clean.\u2014Edwin John\nson arrived from Freeport, Illin\nois, to spend Christmas with his\nparents.\u2014Miss Marian Adams\nwas elected president of a newly\norganized class of Presbyterian\nyoung people.\u2014Esther Zumwin\nkle was named Worthy Matron of\nthe Eastern Star.\n25 YEARS AGO\nWilliam B. Herriott, first editor\nof the Gazette, died at his home\nin Los Angeles at the age of 78.\nThe new Mergenthaler type set\nting machine was installed in the\nGazette office.\u2014Twenty-one per\nsons were initiated into the A. O.\nU. W. Lodge.\u2014Lauterbach broth\ners moved their classy ice cream\nparlor from the old location next\nto D. E. Laird\u2019s hardware store to\nthe Otto Grapp building the third\ndoor north of the postoffice.\u2014W.\nM. Peavey, tailor, installed a fine\nautomatic pressing machine in his\nshop.\u2014Twelve teams started\nhauling gravel from the George\nWhittet pit for the state road west\nof Redwood.\u2014The partnership of\nO. S. Dunham and D. J. Aikin in\nthe stock business was dissolved\nand Dunham continued business.\n\u2014Kenneth Jones, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Horace Jones, was operated\non for cataract in a Minneapolis\nhospital.\u2014T. J. Krell, Redwood\ncounty farmer, sold out and left\nfor California for the winter.\u2014\nMrs. Mary Flinn was in a Los An\ngeles hospital receiving treatment\nfor cataracts.\u2014The teachers of\nrural schools in the county were\npreparing elaborate Christmas\nprograms.\u2014The Sanborn school\nboard decided to do away with\nthe use of common drinking cups\nSee Wards Amazing Values\nGIFTSfeHOMS\n8\nS nfel ,is\n1 1111 l 8\nII High Automatic volume (5 MONTH\nT,T I R|\nroom suite Curley mohair \u00a3Q g,7\\\nand rust tapestry combination. Extended W I ?Iva II il pf fj j\nfront style. 80 inch davenport and club chair. gw ajSSsuLg-jj.\u2014-^1\nDining room suite. Reg. price 84.95. Modern \"WA ST ir\u2014W\nstyle. Burl and stripped walnut veneers. SO yR| M\nf -n. buffet and 70 in. extension table, 6 chairs. 'mM py, B\n(Lounge chair upholstered in brown tapestry. Ifi 93 1 H\nOpen arm style. Built for comfort. I\n9x12 Axminster rugs. Reg. price $49.95. Per- -t&JB 'M (IB\ns'an patterns. Only 2at this price. One in y', %y k Ca.\nrust and one in burgandy. A real value. %mSk Tr _ ~ftC\n9x12 Wilton. Save $25. One only at this ?Q OB l J 1 j QA,*' 3 I t\nprice. Rust and brown, modern design. A yig H\nheavy, serviceable rug at a real saving. m H Down r\nKerosene Range. Save S2O. Automatic wick- 9A QC c 1 H Only\nless, all porcelain. Table top style. Two oil i| H Carrying\ntanks. Ivo~y and black. A real Christmas gift t^e family* 12.5\njjj! i\nJ Prices cut for Christmas! BIG 8| H*W or IT jj jjjj|| j<;\n1 Figured, rayon velvet cover! fi lS ice- Ifp\n(Montgomery Ward\n\u2019fV 200 MILL STREET REDWOOD FALLS TELEPHONE 741 yj\n11\nin the school and installed two\nfountains.\n\n50 YEARS AGO\nMrs. C. C. Peck was visiting re\nlatives in Minneapolis.\u2014Dallas\nLaird was home from Minneapolis\nfor the holidays.\u2014Dr. E. A. Ly\nman Jr. arrived home for the\nholidays.\u2014Mrs. Teed of Renville\nwas visiting here with her daugh\nter Mrs. M. O\u2019Hara.\u2014M. White,\nFrank Boutelle\u2019s father-in-law,\nwas here from his former home in\nDakota.\u2014Thomas Thompson who\nwas working for Byram and com\npany was about to start for Cali\nfornia.\u2014Mrs. Tiffany, the mother\nof J. J. and Charles, was report\ned very ill at the home of the for\nmer.\u2014E. G. Bailey had finished\nhis deer hunt and come home and\nexpected his partner J. B. Mason\nto follow him.\u2014James Anderson\nleft for St. Mary\u2019s, Canada, to\nspend a month with old acquaint\nances and relatives.\u2014Lawyer\nPowell had enough of the Pacific\ncoast and when last heard from\nhad come back as far as Colorado\nwhere he was making a stop.\u2014\nMr. and Mrs. James Barber of\nVesta left for Canada when the\nlatter received notice of the ser\nious illness of a rear relative.\u2014\nMr. and Mrs. P. Worden started\nfrom Topeka, Kansas to Eureka\nSprings where they would remain\nfor the winter.\u2014Among those\nwho were present at the James\nMcMillan home for the dramatic\nclub organization were Mary\nSmith. Flossie Robinson, Lottie\nSchmahl. Jennie Birkenmeyer,\nFannie Everett, Mabel March,\nAnna Smith, Inez Baldwin. Lucy\nRowe. Ora Van Dolah, Charles\nSanderson. H. W. Stewart, L. D.\nWelch, J. F. Skinner, Ross Hauck,\nR. D. White, William French. D.\nR. McCorquodale, O. W. Van\nDolah. S. O. Mason ar.d O. W.\nMcMillan.\nNLa L,ittle\nZMrny 9 Jjim\u2014\nB\nIf winter comes, can spring be\nfar behind?\nWe don\u2019t think so because:\nHarvey Matzener has just got\nhis root beer barrel in working\norder.\nThe rural telephone company is\nprepared for flies just look at\nits screen door!\nEddie Luscher is featuring a\ndisplay of hat pins for the\nwide brimmed garden variety.\nAnd the sign on the side of the\nRedwood Grocery advertises\ntriple-dip ice cream cones.\n(We haven\u2019t checked to see\nwhether Carl Jaehning has his\nstorm windows off yet.)\n\nSaturday afternoon Ole Olson\nwas surprised and dismayed to\nsee a flock of some 50 kids pour\ning into the Montgomery Ward\nstore.\nAnd here\u2019s how it happened.\nThe Redwood Falls Motor com\npany which numbers in its ranks\nsome Men of Genius gave a free\nshow Saturday afternoon. Mobs\nof kids came and stayed and\nstayed and stayed.\nSuddenly someone had an in\nspiration.\nA coin was flipped to see\nwhether the inspiration victims\nshould be Gambles or Wards.\nThe coin decreed Wards, so it\nwas announced that free ice\ncream was being served there.\nEd Johnson, Fox of the Falls,\nrambled home Sunday night after\nlocking up the theatre, only to\nremember when he got there that\nhe had left his car parked in front\nof the establishment.\nSo he trudged back through the\nicy blast.\nNow, Johnson is a man slow to\nanger, but quick to take advant\nage of it. So when he got there,\nhe decided he was pretty mad\nabout his forgetfulness and\nafter deciding, he tore into Har\nvey\u2019s Coffee shop to telephone his\nwife and tell her just how mad\nhe was.\nbig time corn\nTHIEF, NEW JOB\nThe big corn crop and the prac\ntice of storing the grain in open\ncribs on isolated sections of farms\nin southwestern Minnesota and\nlowa has led to farm thefts, ac\ncording to the staff of KNHD.\nThe sheriff of Jackson and an\noperative of the state bureau of\ncriminal apprehension are work\ning on the theft of 250 bushels of\ncorn from an open crib in Jack\nson county last night.\nTuesday 200 bushels were tak\nen from a farm near Round Lake\nin Nobles county, the job having\nthe ear marks of the Jackson\ntheft.","height":"27969","width":"22374"}}
